#, no-wrap
msgid "Patching servers with `dnf-automatic`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:17
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"Managing the installation of security updates is an important matter for the system administrator. The process of providing software updates is a well-trodden path that ultimately causes few problems.\n"
"For these reasons, it is reasonable to automate the download and application of updates daily and automatically on Rocky servers.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:19
#, no-wrap
msgid "The security of your information system will be strengthened. `dnf-automatic` is an additional tool that will allow you to achieve this.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:21
#, no-wrap
msgid "!!! tip \"If you are worried...\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:23
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Years ago, applying updates automatically like this would have been a recipe for disaster. There were many times where an update applied might cause issues. That still happens rarely, when an update of a package removes a deprecated feature that is being used on the server, but for the most part, this simply isn't an issue these days. That said though, if you still feel uncomfortable letting `dnf-automatic` handle the updates, consider using it to download and/or notify you that updates are available. That way your server doesn't remain unpatched for long. These features are `dnf-automatic-notifyonly` and `dnf-automatic-download`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:25
#, no-wrap
msgid "    For more on these features, take a look at the [official documentation](https://dnf.readthedocs.io/en/latest/automatic.html).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:29
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can install `dnf-automatic` from the rocky repositories:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:30
#, no-wrap
msgid "sudo dnf install dnf-automatic\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:37
#, no-wrap
msgid "By default, the update process will start at 6am, with a random extra time delta to avoid all your machines updating at the same time. To change this behavior, you must override the timer configuration associated with the application service:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:38
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"sudo systemctl edit dnf-automatic.timer\n"
"\n"
"[Unit]\n"
"Description=dnf-automatic timer\n"
"# See comment in dnf-makecache.service\n"
"ConditionPathExists=!/run/ostree-booted\n"
"Wants=network-online.target\n"
"\n"
"[Timer]\n"
"OnCalendar=*-*-* 6:00\n"
"RandomizedDelaySec=10m\n"
"Persistent=true\n"
"\n"
"[Install]\n"
"WantedBy=timers.target\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:57
#, no-wrap
msgid "This configuration reduces the start-up delay between 6:00 and 6:10 am. (A server that would be shut down at this time would be automatically patched after its restart.)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:59
#, no-wrap
msgid "Then activate the timer associated to the service (not the service itself):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:60
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ sudo systemctl enable --now dnf-automatic.timer\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:64
#, no-wrap
msgid "What about CentOS 7 servers?"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Yes, this is Rocky Linux documentation, but if you are a system or network administrator, you may have some CentOS 7 machines still in play. We get that, and that is why we are including this section.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:71
#, no-wrap
msgid "The process under CentOS 7 is similar but uses: `yum-cron`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "$ sudo yum install yum-cron\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:77
#, no-wrap
msgid "The configuration of the service is done this time in the file `/etc/yum/yum-cron.conf`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:79
#, no-wrap
msgid "Set configuration as needed:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/dnf_automatic.md:80
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"[commands]\n"
"#  What kind of update to use:\n"
"# default                            = yum upgrade\n"
"# security                           = yum --security upgrade\n"
"# security-severity:Critical         = yum --sec-severity=Critical upgrade\n"
"# minimal                            = yum --bugfix update-minimal\n"
"# minimal-security                   = yum --security update-minimal\n"
"# minimal-security-severity:Critical =  --sec-severity=Critical update-minimal\n"
"update_cmd = default\n"
"\n"
"# Whether a message should be emitted when updates are available,\n"
"# were downloaded, or applied.\n"
"update_messages = yes\n"
"\n"
"# Whether updates should be downloaded when they are available.\n"
"download_updates = yes\n"
"\n"
"# Whether updates should be applied when they are available.  Note\n"
"# that download_updates must also be yes for the update to be applied.\n"
"apply_updates = yes\n"
"\n"
"# Maximum amout of time to randomly sleep, in minutes.  The program\n"
"# will sleep for a random amount of time between 0 and random_sleep\n"
"# minutes before running.  This is useful for e.g. staggering the\n"
"# times that multiple systems will access update servers.  If\n"
"# random_sleep is 0 or negative, the program will run immediately.\n"
"# 6*60 = 360\n"
"random_sleep = 30\n"
msgstr ""

